Climate change netcdf data exploration for Maryland

Lesson Goals¶

in this lesson, you will learn how to calculate seasonal averages over several years using MACA v 2 Climate Data downloaded in netcdf4 format using xarray. In this example you will use the forecast temperature data downloaded from the northwestknowledge.net website.

Prerequests¶

  1. Install the below mentioned libraries

NB:make sure for possible update of software modules, libraries. this lesson prepare by using anaconda 3.7.1

# Would this be better if it only returned 4 values?? probably so
# Helper Function to extract AOI
def get_aoi(shp, world=True):
    """Takes a geopandas object and converts it to a lat/ lon
    extent """

    lon_lat = {}
    # Get lat min, max
    aoi_lat = [float(shp.total_bounds[1]), float(shp.total_bounds[3])]
    aoi_lon = [float(shp.total_bounds[0]), float(shp.total_bounds[2])]

    # Handle the 0-360 lon values
    if world:
        aoi_lon[0] = aoi_lon[0] + 360
        aoi_lon[1] = aoi_lon[1] + 360
    lon_lat["lon"] = aoi_lon
    lon_lat["lat"] = aoi_lat
    return lon_lat

# Get lat min, max from mary aoi extent
mary_bounds = get_aoi(mary_aoi)

# Slice by time & aoi location
start_date = "2018-12-15"
end_date = "2050-12-15"

mary_temp = monthly_forecast_temp_xr["air_temperature"].sel(
    time=slice(start_date, end_date),
    lon=slice(mary_bounds["lon"][0], mary_bounds["lon"][1]),
    lat=slice(mary_bounds["lat"][0], mary_bounds["lat"][1]))

# Create the region mask object - this is used to identify each region
mary_region = regionmask.from_geopandas(mary_aoi,
                                        names="name",
                                       name="name",
                                       abbrevs="iso_3166_2")
mary_mask = regionmask.mask_3D_geopandas(mary_aoi,
                                         monthly_forecast_temp_xr.lon,
                                         monthly_forecast_temp_xr.lat)
# Mask the netcdf data
mary_temp_masked = mary_temp.where(mary_mask)

Calculate UnWeighted Seasonal Averages For By Season Across Each Year¶

In [41]:
# Resample the data by season across all years
mary_season_mean_all_years = mary_temp_masked.resample(
    time='QS-DEC', skipna=False, keep_attrs=True).mean()
mary_season_mean_all_years.shape

# Summarize each array into one single (mean) value
mary_seasonal_mean = mary_season_mean_all_years.groupby('time').mean([
    "lat", "lon"])

Plot Seasonal Data By Season¶

In [46]:
colors = {3: "grey", 6: "lightgreen", 9: "green", 12: "purple"}

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 7))
for month, arr in mary_seasonal_mean.groupby('time.month'):
    arr.plot(ax=ax,
             color="grey",
             marker="o",
             markerfacecolor=colors[month],
             markeredgecolor=colors[month],
             label=seasons[month])

                      month_length.resample(time='QS-DEC').sum())
